Electronic Waste Recycling Attitudes and Intentions among Swiss Households

Capstone Project

Author
Affiliation

Leo Meili

ETH Zurich

Published

June 5, 2025

Abstract
In this project, the recycling attitudes of Swiss households are evaluated. It is further examined if targeted information on ethical controversies associated with critical raw material mining can influence said recycling intentions.

Introduction

Electronic waste (e-waste) is a fast-growing solid waste stream with a large portion only being recycled informally(Liu et al. 2023). This is problematic for the recyclers and the environment due to its toxicity (Heacock et al. 2016; Perkins et al. 2014). As the economic value can also still be high for e-waste, its recycling can also be interesting from an economic and geopolitical viewpoint (Cucchiella et al. 2015). This is highlighted with the EU defining the so-called critical raw materials (CRM) act (âEuropean Critical Raw Materials Act - European Commissionâ 2023).

Methods

To determine general attitudes of Swiss households on e-waste recycling, a survey asking participants to express their agreement with recycling-related statements based on the Likert Scale was created. This included factors contributing to the case for comprehensive e-waste recycling, general personal recycling attitudes and intentions, and rating the recycling of different materials. All participants unaware of the term CRM were informed of its meaning. Additionally, a randomized group of the participants were shown an article highlighting some of the dire conditions associated with artisanal cobalt mining in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), and Cobaltâs use in electronics today (Huff 2023). It was hypothesized that e-waste recycling intentions and attitudes of this group would be greater than that of the control group.

Results

As can be seen in TableÂ 1, all participants reported to have e-waste lying around at home, with an average of 6 items.

The familiarity with the term critical raw material on the other hand was rather low (FigureÂ 1), with only 16% having heard of it before taking the survey.

After that, the survey split into the two groups, hereafter referred to as the control and the CRM group. The recycling attitudes were found to be very similar for both groups, with no significant difference between the ones shown the additional info on CRM to the control group. In FigureÂ 2, the importance of certain factors in the case for recycling e-waste showed to be largely unaffected by what group the respondent was in. Overall, the provided factors were evaluated similarly to each other, namely as being very to extremely important.
The control group often evaluated reasons to be more important for recycling e-waste than the CRM group. Whatâs especially relevant is that they did that also for âreducing dependence on ethically controversial miningâ, the main topic of the article shown to the CRM group.

This therefore does not allow for a statement on the effectiveness or influence of providing such additional information. It should be mentioned however that the control group consisted only of 7 participants (CRM group: 14 participants), so its statistical relevance is in any way inexistent.

As seen in FigureÂ 3 and FigureÂ 4, similar results were found for overall recycling importance, intentions and when comparing different materialsâ recycling. No trend indicating higher importance and intentions for the CRM groups are recognisable. If anything, itâs worth mentioning that the control group deemed e-waste recycling more important than the CRM group, but did so with most types of material recycling, so this could also be attributed to overall higher motivation to recycle.


Nevertheless, recycling intentions are high to very high and personal importance is weighted a bit higher than systemic importance of recycling e-waste. The attitudes reflect that the need for recycling, especially e-waste, is widespread, with metal and PET being evaluated in a similar fashion, organic waste, paper/cardboard and glass slightly lower.

A visualization of the demographics of the surveyâs participants can be found in the Appendix, FigureÂ 5.

Conclusion

  • Recycling intentions and attitudes towards e-waste are very high among the surveyâs respondents, mainly young, highly educated people living in shared apartments.

  • Including targeted information on CRM and its ethically controversial sourcing in countries like the DRC did not show any significant effect on e-waste recycling intentions and attitudes.

  • This is mainly attributed to the statistically insignificant amount of responses of either group and the high education level of participants.
